            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ramon Santos-Miller is a product of the San Francisco that exists beneath the shiny veneer of tech wealth. Born in Daly City to Elena, a compassionate nurse from the Philippines, and David, a quiet, union-proud American longshoreman, Ramon grew up straddling two worlds. His childhood was filled with the aroma of his mother's adobo, the sound of the foghorns rolling over the hills, and a deep-seated understanding of the value of hard work and community support.\n\nHis path seemed set when he enrolled at SF State, pursuing a degree in Social and Human Services. However, the AIDS crisis of the late \u201880s and early \u201890s shattered his academic focus. Witnessing the devastation firsthand, Ramon felt an overwhelming pull to act rather than study. He left college, just a few credits shy of his degree, to volunteer full-time at a clinic in the Castro. This trial by fire became his true education, forging a fierce dedication to frontline care that has defined his life. That experience is where he met his late husband, Mark Miller, an equally passionate community organizer. They combined their names upon marrying, a symbol of their united front against the world\u2019s injustices.\n\nNow 54 and a widower for five years, Ramon channels his grief into his work as a Community Health Case Manager. His days are a blur of navigating bureaucracy for families in need, connecting students with mental health resources, and advocating for those the system overlooks. He lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Mission, the same neighborhood he's worked in for decades. His 1.5-mile commute on the 14 Mission bus is a daily ritual, a rolling microcosm of the city he serves.\n\nRamon\u2019s aspirations are not for wealth or recognition, but for a city that cares for its own. He dreams of seeing social safety nets strengthened and hopes to one day travel to his mother\u2019s home province in the Philippines, a trip he and Mark always planned to take. His life is a testament to quiet resilience, a deep, abiding love for San Francisco's enduring, complicated soul."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being eight years old in Daly City, the kitchen warm with the smell of his mother\u2019s adobo while the fog swallowed the world outside. His father would come home from the docks, his hands calloused from work, and silently eat. It wasn't just food; it was a ritual of care, a promise that no matter how harsh it was outside, inside they looked after each other. That feeling of quiet, essential support became the blueprint for his entire life.\n\n2.\nAt 21, his SF State textbooks felt like a betrayal. He stood inside the Castro clinic for the first time, the air thick with fear and lavender disinfectant, and saw a young man his age crying silently in a corner. In that instant, every theory on social services collapsed into one devastating, human reality. The choice was brutally simple: study the crisis or fight it. He never went back to campus. His real education had just begun.\n\n3.\nIt was 3 AM at the clinic, a rare moment of quiet in the storm. Mark found him, handed him a cup of stale coffee, and just sat with him in the hallway. They didn\u2019t have to speak. In Mark\u2019s tired eyes, Ramon saw the same fierce, stubborn compassion that fueled him. It wasn\u2019t a spark; it was a profound recognition. In the midst of so much loss, he found a partner and knew he wasn't fighting alone anymore.\n\n4.\nA week after Mark died, a form required his signature. He wrote \u2018Ramon Santos-Miller,\u2019 and the hyphen felt like a physical wound, a bridge to a man who was gone. He stared at the name they had built together, a symbol of their united front. The grief was a tidal wave, but beneath it was a bedrock of resolve. The work was not just his anymore\u2014it was theirs. And he would carry it forward for them both.\n\n5.\nOn the 14 Mission bus last week, he watched the city wake up. A mother soothing her child in Tagalog, a construction worker nodding off, a young artist sketching furiously. For a moment, the weight of his caseloads felt lighter. These weren't just clients or statistics; they were his neighbors, the city's pulsing heart. This daily journey is his pilgrimage, a 1.5-mile reminder of the complicated, resilient soul he refuses to give up on."
